newsitem.title: UK: NWE naphtha edges higher, but end-users sidelined.
newsitem.headline: NWE naphtha edges higher, but end-users sidelined.

text.p: NWE naphtha prices were steady to slightly higher on Wednesday but end-user demand was lacklustre and traders said the market continued to nestle into contango.
"It really is calm for the physical market from the end-users," one source said. "If there is interest it is more for January...There is not much discussion for prompt material."
A 6,000 tonne Russian piece was believed placed on Tuesday at a discount, further reflecting the weakness in prompt prices to early January, he said.
Jan swaps confirmed traded at $224, up $2 while Feb was seen $1 higher at $217/$218.
NWE cargoes were notionally set at about $219/$223 cif, but traders said no physical deals were done and would likely be done at lower levels.
Bids for pipeline spec material heard earlier in the week at higher levels to cargoes, appeared to disappear by today, they said.
Shipping sources said Dow fixed the World Process tanker for 27,500 tonnes of naphtha out of Skikda on Dec 20 for the U.K./Continent.
Stinnes fixed the Rose for 27,000 tonnes out of Ras Lanuf on Dec 28 for Brindisi, Italy, they said.
